{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8ad6baf9-f5e3-4246-a529-37e5bae319e9","content":"The most likely cause: **.NET MAUI Android ignores `JAVA_HOME`**. It uses its own JDK path (typically the Microsoft OpenJDK installed with the Android workload), not the one in your environment.\n\n**Fix — choose one:**\n\n1. **Tell MSBuild explicitly:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"$JAVA_HOME\"\n   ```\n\n2. **Or set it in your `.csproj`:**\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup Condition=\"'$(TargetFramework)' == 'net8.0-android'\">\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>$(JAVA_HOME)</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Or install the expected JDK** (recommended — avoids drift):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet workload install maui-android\n   ```\n   This installs the Microsoft OpenJDK 17 the toolchain expects. It lands at:\n   ```\n   /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n   ```\n\nIf you share the actual error message, I can give a more targeted diagnosis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c3027f9f-59dd-416c-9b8d-c49f150cf5ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the issue likely is.\n\n.NET MAUI Android builds use Gradle/Android SDK tools under the hood. The common Java-related issue with .NET MAUI Android builds is about the JDK version compatibility.\n\nKey facts:\n- .NET 8+ MAUI requires JDK 17\n- They have JDK 17.0.12 — so the version itself should be fine\n- But there's a known issue: .NET MAUI/Android SDK specifically requires the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution, not just any JDK 17\n\n\n- The .NET Android workload ships with Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and when JAVA_HOME points to a different distribution like Adoptium Temurin, it can cause build failures\n- On macOS specifically, the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property needs to point to the correct JDK location\n\n, and JAVA_HOME might need the full path like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`\n- The real issue is likely that .NET MAUI wants to use its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK, but the JAVA_HOME override to Temurin is either creating a conflict or not being picked up by the build system at all\n\nWithout seeing the actual error message, I'm working with the most common scenarios - usually it's either a version mismatch between what .NET MAUI expects and what's installed, or the build system simply isn't finding the JDK correctly on macOS. JAVA_HOME points to it. Common issues:\n\n1. The .NET Android SDK might not be finding the JDK despite JAVA_HOME being set - on macOS this is often because the IDE (VS for Mac, Rider) has its own JDK settings.\n\n2. The error could be related to `JAVA_HOME` pointing to a JRE instead of a JDK (but Temurin installs a full JDK).\n\n3. There could be a path issue - on macOS with Adoptium Temurin, the path is typically `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n\n.NET MAUI specifically requires JDK 17 and looks for it through the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, so if they have multiple JDKs installed or the build system isn't respecting JAVA_HOME, that's likely the culprit. The real fix usually involves explicitly setting `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` to point to the Temurin installation. The most common issue is that .NET MAUI Android builds use Microsoft's bundled OpenJDK by default rather than respecting the JAVA_HOME environment variable, so I need to guide the user toward explicitly configuring the JavaSdkDirectory property to point to their JDK installation.","outputTokens":2038},"id":"2db80c69-45f8-48ec-b4b1-8a0583a3e941","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:47:49.930Z","parentId":"6a272b36-feae-40a9-8051-95e66228c1f3"}
